l element in consumer capitalism and a practice that has always been shaped by queer sensibilities. By outlining the paradox that queerness lies at the center of capitalist heteronormativity and telling the largely unknown story of queer models and photographers, Brown offers an out of the ordinary history of twentieth-century American culture and capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aCommercial photographyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFashion photographyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFemininity in popular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aModels (Persons)zUnited States. 0aPhotography of womenxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aQueer theory. 0aSex in advertisingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen in popular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPhotography / Subjects & Themes / Fashion.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478002147zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478002147423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478002147.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles